          "raw_response": "{\n  \"final_bugs\": [\n    {\n      \"description\": \"The algorithm applies the slip b_v even when the frog lands at ground level (depth 0). According to the problem, after reaching depth 0 the frog stops and does not slip. The code treats v == 0 like any other landing depth, computing new_pos = 0 + b[0] and thus never reaches dp[0] correctly.\",\n      \"triggering_input\": \"3\\n0 2 2\\n1 1 0\\n\",\n      \"fix\": \"When v == 0, set new_pos = 0 (or simply update dp[0] without adding slip) and do not push further states from 0. In the BFS loop, handle the case v == 0 separately, e.g.:\\n```python\\nif v == 0:\\n    if dp[0] > dp[u] + 1:\\n        dp[0] = dp[u] + 1\\n        q.append(0)\\nelse:\\n    new_pos = v + b[v]\\n    if dp[new_pos] > dp[u] + 1:\\n        dp[new_pos] = dp[u] + 1\\n        q.append(new_pos)\\n```\",\n      \"confirmed\": true,\n      \"reasoning\": \"With the original code the BFS never updates dp[0] for the sample where the optimal path ends with a jump to depth 0, resulting in output -1 instead of the correct answer.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"description\": \"Path reconstruction assumes every transition involves a slip (v + b[v] == current). The final jump ends at depth 0 without a slip, so the condition fails and the algorithm cannot backtrack the last step, producing an empty or incorrect path.\",\n      \"triggering_input\": \"3\\n0 2 2\\n1 1 0\\n\",\n      \"fix\": \"Store predecessor information during BFS (e.g., an array prev[current] = v) for every state, handling the special case v == 0. Then rebuild the path by following prev from 0 back to n and reverse it. Alternatively, modify the reconstruction loop to treat current == 0 specially:\\n```python\\nwhile current != n:\\n    if current == 0:\\n        # find v such that v + b[v] == previous state and dp[v] == dp[0] - 1\\n        for v in range(n, -1, -1):\\n            if v + b[v] == prev_state and dp[v] == dp[0] - 1:\\n                path.append(v)\\n                current = v\\n                break\\n    else:\\n        for v in range(n, -1, -1):\\n            if v + b[v] == current and dp[v] == dp[current] - 1:\\n                path.append(v)\\n                current = v\\n                break\\n```\",\n      \"confirmed\": true,\n      \"reasoning\": \"The original reconstruction loop never finds a predecessor for current == 0 because the condition v + b[v] == 0 cannot be satisfied (b[0] is undefined for depth 0). Hence it fails to output the required sequence of landing depths.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"description\": \"The BFS iterates over all possible landing depths v in the interval [u - a_u, u] for each visited state u. In the worst case (e.g., a_i = i for all i) this leads to O(n\u00b2) operations, which is far too slow for n up to 300\u202f000 and will cause a time\u2011limit exceeded.\",\n      \"triggering_input\": \"300000\\n\" + \" \".join(str(i) for i in range(1, 300001)) + \"\\n\" + \" \".join(\"0\" for _ in range(300000)) + \"\\n\",\n      \"fix\": \"Replace the na\u00efve loop with a data structure that can retrieve and remove all unvisited positions in a given interval efficiently. A common solution is to keep a set (e.g., a balanced BST or a sorted list) of all unvisited depths and, for each u, repeatedly find the smallest v in the set that lies in [u - a_u, u], process it, and erase it. This makes the total work O(n log n). Example using a sorted container:\\n```python\\nimport bisect\\nunvisited = list(range(n + 1))\\n# use a sorted list or a tree\u2011based set\\nwhile q:\\n    u = q.popleft()\\n    left = u - a[u - 1]\\n    while True:\\n        i = bisect.bisect_left(unvisited, left)\\n        if i == len(unvisited) or unvisited[i] > u:\\n            break\\n        v = unvisited.pop(i)\\n        # process v as before\\n```\",\n      \"confirmed\": true,\n      \"reasoning\": \"The original double loop can iterate up to O(n) times for each of O(n) states, which is unacceptable for the maximal input size.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}",
